WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.360 --> 00:00:04.890
Prof: Okay,
let's start in.

00:00:04.890 --> 00:00:11.250
Got a fairly large agenda today.
 

00:00:11.250 --> 00:00:15.328
And I wanted to remind you that
next week, we're moving on to

00:00:15.328 --> 00:00:16.280
air quality.
 

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:22.091
So check your syllabus and read
the material for section next

00:00:22.091 --> 00:00:22.770
week.
 

00:00:22.770 --> 00:00:28.220
And today I want to talk about
two principles in law,

00:00:28.220 --> 00:00:31.440
one being preemption and the
other being defamation,

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:34.400
and to give you a couple of
case histories.

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:38.262
And I'm going to start out
talking about Bates v.

00:00:38.262 --> 00:00:39.020
Dow.
 

00:00:39.020 --> 00:00:43.256
And then I want to talk about
two cases, one,

00:00:43.256 --> 00:00:48.166
product disparagement,
and the other one is known as

00:00:48.166 --> 00:00:49.900
the Alar case.
 

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:53.778
And another is a case that was
brought by the Texas Cattlemen's

00:00:53.778 --> 00:00:56.030
Association against Oprah
Winfrey.

00:00:56.030 --> 00:01:01.890
And I'll show you a couple of
video clips of that.

00:01:01.890 --> 00:01:05.512
First of all,
preemption has its origin in

00:01:05.512 --> 00:01:08.819
the Constitution,
within the supremacy clause

00:01:08.819 --> 00:01:10.826
that states,
"This Constitution and the

00:01:10.826 --> 00:01:11.489
laws of the U.S.
 

00:01:11.489 --> 00:01:14.477
shall be the supreme law of the
land, and the judges in every

00:01:14.477 --> 00:01:16.319
state shall be bound
thereby."

00:01:16.319 --> 00:01:20.566
So that within air quality law,
within pesticide management

00:01:20.566 --> 00:01:23.438
law,
within pharmaceutical law,

00:01:23.438 --> 00:01:26.296
tobacco law,
occupational law,

00:01:26.296 --> 00:01:31.617
states are prohibited from
adopting certain standards that

00:01:31.617 --> 00:01:35.819
are different than the federal
government.

00:01:35.819 --> 00:01:40.128
And the purpose behind this is
not to create a patchwork quilt

00:01:40.128 --> 00:01:44.084
that is really comprised of
non-uniform standards so that

00:01:44.084 --> 00:01:48.534
when corporations wish to trade
goods or provide services across

00:01:48.534 --> 00:01:51.690
state boundaries,
they basically have the

00:01:51.690 --> 00:01:52.580
expectations.
 

00:01:52.580 --> 00:01:56.304
It's often applied to
situations that are risky or

00:01:56.304 --> 00:01:58.280
products that are risky.
 

00:01:58.280 --> 00:02:02.129
And the failure to warn is
often a key question.

00:02:02.129 --> 00:02:04.769
And we'll raise that in the
case today.

00:02:04.769 --> 00:02:08.490
With respect to pesticides,
Congress traditionally deferred

00:02:08.490 --> 00:02:11.889
to states to regulate threats to
health and safety.

00:02:11.889 --> 00:02:15.337
But since 1970,
it's exercised its power to

00:02:15.337 --> 00:02:20.098
preempt state or local
regulation in a number of areas,

00:02:20.098 --> 00:02:25.288
particularly with respect to
warning labels on pesticides.

00:02:25.288 --> 00:02:28.360
So there are a variety of
theories of damage recovery.

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:33.783
So if you imagine that say
someone comes to your home and

00:02:33.783 --> 00:02:39.596
promises to give you a green
lawn by applying fertilizers and

00:02:39.596 --> 00:02:43.979
insecticides,
and all of a sudden you notice

00:02:43.979 --> 00:02:47.150
an acrid taste in your well
water,

00:02:47.150 --> 00:02:54.800
and also your children start to
feel awkward or strange.

00:02:54.800 --> 00:02:57.797
And you find out that the
chemicals that were applied were

00:02:57.797 --> 00:02:59.060
neurotoxic substances.
 

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:01.860
And what are your rights?
 

00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:06.770
Basically, you could argue
that-- we have percussion

00:03:06.770 --> 00:03:11.513
section out there on the street,
throwing I think rocks or

00:03:11.513 --> 00:03:13.930
bricks into one of these big
metal barrels.

00:03:13.930 --> 00:03:16.550
So I apologize for that.
 

00:03:16.550 --> 00:03:20.403
So you can imagine yourself in
a situation where you conclude

00:03:20.403 --> 00:03:23.680
that federal law didn't protect
you against that.

00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:25.068
You feel like you've been
damaged.

00:03:25.068 --> 00:03:28.122
It's going to cost you money to
either drill a new well or to

00:03:28.122 --> 00:03:29.598
put infiltration equipment.
 

00:03:29.598 --> 00:03:32.300
And what about the health
effects on your family?

00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:37.120
So there are a variety of
theories of damage recovery.

00:03:37.120 --> 00:03:41.610
And one is that the failure to
warn provides a justification

00:03:41.610 --> 00:03:44.199
for seeking recovery of damages.
 

00:03:44.199 --> 00:03:49.615
So remember what I argued about
the difficulty that most people

00:03:49.615 --> 00:03:53.110
have in understanding warning
labels,

00:03:53.110 --> 00:03:56.129
the difficulty of taking
complicated scientific

00:03:56.129 --> 00:03:59.675
information and reducing it in a
way that would make it

00:03:59.675 --> 00:04:03.025
intelligible and make you
capable of knowing how you

00:04:03.025 --> 00:04:05.979
should behave in order to
prevent risk.

00:04:05.979 --> 00:04:08.919
For example,
should you be responsible to

00:04:08.919 --> 00:04:13.403
know that you have sandy soils
and that your well is a shallow

00:04:13.403 --> 00:04:14.979
well,
and it's an old well,

00:04:14.979 --> 00:04:16.060
and the casing is cracked?
 

00:04:16.060 --> 00:04:18.579
I mean, are you really
responsible to know that?

00:04:18.579 --> 00:04:21.089
Should that information be on a
warning label?

00:04:21.089 --> 00:04:24.120
Negligence is another theory
for recovery.

00:04:24.120 --> 00:04:29.375
So was the product made in a
negligent way or was it used in

00:04:29.375 --> 00:04:30.980
a negligent way?
 

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:32.959
How about design defects?
 

00:04:32.959 --> 00:04:36.550
Listening to Good Morning
America today,

00:04:36.550 --> 00:04:40.949
I was intrigued by litigation
that is growing,

00:04:40.949 --> 00:04:45.161
class action suits against
Toyota because of their

00:04:45.161 --> 00:04:49.500
accelerator pad catching,
or brake defects.

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:54.627
So some defect in production or
design that leads to a higher

00:04:54.627 --> 00:04:59.668
level, higher concentration of
risk or hazard and subsequent

00:04:59.668 --> 00:05:00.610
damage.
 

00:05:00.610 --> 00:05:03.850
How about failure to disclose
incident reports?

00:05:03.850 --> 00:05:08.353
So that Dow Chemical Company
was fined nearly $800,000

00:05:08.353 --> 00:05:13.367
because it had been reported to
Dow by a variety of families

00:05:13.367 --> 00:05:17.956
that they felt that they had
medical problems that were

00:05:17.956 --> 00:05:21.610
associated with using their
products.

00:05:21.610 --> 00:05:26.083
And they were required under
federal pesticide law to report

00:05:26.083 --> 00:05:30.860
those incidents back to the
Environmental Protection Agency,

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:33.500
and they did not do so within
the time limit,

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:36.139
there was a significant delay.
 

00:05:36.139 --> 00:05:38.410
So the failure to disclose
incident reports.

00:05:38.410 --> 00:05:43.759
And again, with the auto
defects that we're witnessing in

00:05:43.759 --> 00:05:49.779
the press and in the showrooms
today, the same issue applies.

00:05:49.779 --> 00:05:54.190
So when did the corporation
know that the pedals stuck or

00:05:54.190 --> 00:05:58.129
that the brake system was not
working correctly?

00:05:58.129 --> 00:06:02.293
So the failure to report back
to government agencies that have

00:06:02.293 --> 00:06:06.634
regulatory responsibilities,
whether it's pharmaceuticals or

00:06:06.634 --> 00:06:09.720
cars or pesticides or cosmetics
or foods,

00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:13.560
these generally carry
significant penalties.

00:06:13.560 --> 00:06:18.451
And because of preemption
that's built into pesticide law

00:06:18.451 --> 00:06:23.449
and air quality law,
et cetera, states have often

00:06:23.449 --> 00:06:29.752
denied access to courts to use
these theories of recovery to

00:06:29.752 --> 00:06:32.209
secure compensation.
 

00:06:32.209 --> 00:06:37.519
So the state courts have often
not agreed to hear the cases.

00:06:37.519 --> 00:06:39.379
This is why Bates v.
 

00:06:39.379 --> 00:06:41.399
Dow is so important.
 

00:06:41.399 --> 00:06:45.798
Bates is a case in which
twenty-nine peanut growers in

00:06:45.798 --> 00:06:49.865
Texas alleged that Dow
AgroSciences had produced a

00:06:49.865 --> 00:06:52.440
chemical called Strong Arm.
 

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:57.285
Strong Arm, they claimed
damaged their peanut plants back

00:06:57.285 --> 00:06:58.930
in the year 2000.
 

00:06:58.930 --> 00:07:03.687
And the pesticide label itself
claimed that "Use of Strong

00:07:03.687 --> 00:07:08.600
Arm is recommended in all areas
where peanuts are grown."

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:12.050
Now, when it was used in the
Texas peanut farmland,

00:07:12.050 --> 00:07:15.449
where the soils exceeded a pH
of seven point two,

00:07:15.449 --> 00:07:18.612
it damaged both the peanut
crop, and it failed to control

00:07:18.612 --> 00:07:19.290
the weeds.
 

00:07:19.290 --> 00:07:23.545
So the activity of this
chemical is mediated by the

00:07:23.545 --> 00:07:25.420
acidity of the soil.
 

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:28.800
And by 2001,
EPA had approved a new label

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:31.656
for the chemical,
including a new warning,

00:07:31.656 --> 00:07:34.379
"Do not apply Strong Arm
to soils with a pH of seven

00:07:34.379 --> 00:07:35.839
point two or greater."
 

00:07:35.839 --> 00:07:38.980
So this case was decided in
2005.

00:07:38.980 --> 00:07:45.437
This label was in force for
four years before the decision

00:07:45.437 --> 00:07:46.230
date.
 

00:07:46.230 --> 00:07:49.420
So eventually,
the case wound its way up to

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:50.940
the Supreme Court.
 

00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:53.839
And this is quite a feat.
 

00:07:53.839 --> 00:07:57.396
In many instances,
claims that are brought in

00:07:57.396 --> 00:08:02.329
state courts do not make their
way up to the Supreme Court.

00:08:02.329 --> 00:08:06.201
It can often take decades or
even a half a century before a

00:08:06.201 --> 00:08:09.738
case is believed to be
appropriate for judicial review

00:08:09.738 --> 00:08:12.410
by the highest court in the
country.

00:08:12.410 --> 00:08:15.012
So they found that
"Congress surely would have

00:08:15.012 --> 00:08:17.666
expressed its intent more
clearly of it had meant to

00:08:17.666 --> 00:08:20.269
deprive injured parties of a
long-available form of

00:08:20.269 --> 00:08:21.259
compensation.
 

00:08:21.259 --> 00:08:23.961
Moreover, this history
emphasizes the importance of

00:08:23.961 --> 00:08:26.985
providing an incentive to
manufacturers to use the utmost

00:08:26.985 --> 00:08:30.120
care in distributing inherently
dangerous items."

00:08:30.120 --> 00:08:34.275
In other words,
the Supreme Court was looking

00:08:34.275 --> 00:08:39.000
at these lawsuits to seek
recovery as really a last

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:40.038
resort.
 

00:08:40.038 --> 00:08:42.750
So it represents the failure of
federal law,

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:46.432
it represents the failure of
state law or local law to offer

00:08:46.432 --> 00:08:49.615
sufficient environmental
protection or protection of

00:08:49.615 --> 00:08:50.740
public health.
 

00:08:50.740 --> 00:08:53.038
So what's a damaged party to do?
 

00:08:53.038 --> 00:08:55.360
What are you going to do if
you've been damaged?

00:08:55.360 --> 00:08:58.908
Well, you probably would
consider litigation.

00:08:58.908 --> 00:09:02.825
So the Supreme Court continued,
"It seems unlikely that

00:09:02.825 --> 00:09:06.938
Congress considered a relatively
obscure provision like Section

00:09:06.938 --> 00:09:10.589
136VB (which is the preemption
clause) to give pesticide

00:09:10.589 --> 00:09:14.304
manufacturers virtual immunity
from certain forms of tort

00:09:14.304 --> 00:09:15.500
liability.
 

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:19.370
And we've been pointed to no
evidence that such tort suits

00:09:19.370 --> 00:09:22.836
led to a crazy quilt of FIFRA
(federal pesticide law

00:09:22.836 --> 00:09:26.368
standards) or otherwise created
any real hardship for

00:09:26.368 --> 00:09:28.610
manufacturers or EPA."
 

00:09:28.610 --> 00:09:33.126
So the argument that you would
have an uneven regulatory

00:09:33.126 --> 00:09:37.808
playing field among the states
had no substance to it,

00:09:37.808 --> 00:09:43.437
or that the manufacturers would
be damaged significantly by

00:09:43.437 --> 00:09:46.952
these claims,
because they're expensive,

00:09:46.952 --> 00:09:51.428
they're time consuming,
and few people actually have

00:09:51.428 --> 00:09:55.960
the resources or capacity to
bring the lawsuits.

00:09:55.960 --> 00:09:58.849
So central questions today
really will involve a question

00:09:58.849 --> 00:10:02.048
of freedom of speech and when is
it appropriate to limit speech

00:10:02.048 --> 00:10:04.320
about environmental and health
hazards,

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:06.408
intellectual property rights.
 

00:10:06.408 --> 00:10:11.600
Who should own the right to
knowledge of risk?

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:18.288
Should corporations be capable
of holding that as a secret?

00:10:18.288 --> 00:10:22.423
Or should they be obligated to
disclose that to the public in

00:10:22.423 --> 00:10:26.351
the form of a warning label or a
disclosure of an incident

00:10:26.351 --> 00:10:27.110
report?
 

00:10:27.110 --> 00:10:30.210
What should the standard of
proof be?

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:33.480
And how should the falsity of a
statement be judged?

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:37.149
The falsity of a statement on a
label or the falsity of a

00:10:37.149 --> 00:10:40.950
statement made by a party that
is challenging a corporation

00:10:40.950 --> 00:10:44.620
that they were damaged by
exposure to their product?

00:10:44.620 --> 00:10:46.220
And where should the burden of
proof lie?

00:10:46.220 --> 00:10:49.841
Should the burden of proof lie
with the plaintiff to prove the

00:10:49.841 --> 00:10:52.929
falsity of criticism,
or the defendant to prove truth

00:10:52.929 --> 00:10:53.940
of criticism?
 

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:58.946
And to explore this area of
product disparagement more

00:10:58.946 --> 00:11:02.820
fully, I want you to consider
one case.

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:07.879
This is a case of a chemical
known as Alar that you probably

00:11:07.879 --> 00:11:09.678
did not experience.
 

00:11:09.678 --> 00:11:13.730
But it was in wide use in the
United States and in different

00:11:13.730 --> 00:11:17.299
parts of the world back in the
1980s and early 1990s,

00:11:17.299 --> 00:11:19.360
and it was used on apples.
 

00:11:19.360 --> 00:11:23.302
And it was used on apple
orchards basically to cause stem

00:11:23.302 --> 00:11:25.855
thickening,
so it would hold the apple on

00:11:25.855 --> 00:11:29.096
the tree longer and it would
keep the apple from falling down

00:11:29.096 --> 00:11:30.340
and getting bruised.
 

00:11:30.340 --> 00:11:33.408
So it would maintain the
commercial quality and the grade

00:11:33.408 --> 00:11:34.230
of the apple.
 

00:11:34.230 --> 00:11:37.100
And it would also cause uniform
ripening.

00:11:37.100 --> 00:11:39.860
Uniform ripening is important,
because you don't want part of

00:11:39.860 --> 00:11:41.570
a tree,
perhaps that's facing the

00:11:41.570 --> 00:11:44.239
sunshine,
to have apples that are ripe

00:11:44.239 --> 00:11:49.082
and then all the apples that are
on the north side of the tree in

00:11:49.082 --> 00:11:51.960
more shade that would remain
green.

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:56.539
So it provided economic
advantage to orchard owners in a

00:11:56.539 --> 00:11:58.038
variety of ways.
 

00:11:58.038 --> 00:12:02.100
This is a systemic compound,
which is interesting.

00:12:02.100 --> 00:12:06.020
It means that it's absorbed up
through the plant roots itself

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:07.590
into the plant tissue.
 

00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:10.811
So you may think that some
residues are only on the surface

00:12:10.811 --> 00:12:14.254
of a fruit or a vegetable and if
you peel it or if you wash it,

00:12:14.254 --> 00:12:15.808
you could get rid of it.
 

00:12:15.808 --> 00:12:20.726
Here's an example of a compound
that that would not be helpful

00:12:20.726 --> 00:12:21.210
for.
 

00:12:21.210 --> 00:12:23.070
It's not easy to detect.
 

00:12:23.070 --> 00:12:28.568
When this chemical was being
reviewed and became a public

00:12:28.568 --> 00:12:32.889
target for criticism of its
manufacturer,

00:12:32.889 --> 00:12:35.288
I went up to the state of
Massachusetts,

00:12:35.288 --> 00:12:37.254
because the state of
Massachusetts was trying to

00:12:37.254 --> 00:12:39.470
figure out if they were going to
ban the compound,

00:12:39.470 --> 00:12:42.970
as it was detected increasingly
in foods.

00:12:42.970 --> 00:12:44.798
And I went to their
laboratories,

00:12:44.798 --> 00:12:47.996
their state laboratories,
and they had not even developed

00:12:47.996 --> 00:12:49.538
a detection method yet.
 

00:12:49.538 --> 00:12:52.549
Speaking to their analytic
chemists, they didn't even know

00:12:52.549 --> 00:12:54.029
how to find this in foods.
 

00:12:54.029 --> 00:12:56.210
So think about that for a
minute.

00:12:56.210 --> 00:13:00.202
What that means is that the
government approved the use of a

00:13:00.202 --> 00:13:03.924
chemical on certain crops when
it knew that there was no

00:13:03.924 --> 00:13:07.918
accepted method for detecting it
in the food or in processed

00:13:07.918 --> 00:13:11.640
forms of the food or in water
supplies if it happened to

00:13:11.640 --> 00:13:14.009
contaminate water supplies.
 

00:13:14.009 --> 00:13:18.543
So that's quite curious and it
might give you some ideas about

00:13:18.543 --> 00:13:22.778
prior requirements before
introducing new technologies.

00:13:22.778 --> 00:13:29.149
So it has an unusual
characteristic.

00:13:29.149 --> 00:13:32.404
It produces unsymmetrical
dimethylhydrazine,

00:13:32.404 --> 00:13:35.962
UDMH, which is also a space
shuttle rocket fuel,

00:13:35.962 --> 00:13:40.429
but only under conditions where
the chemical is heated.

00:13:40.429 --> 00:13:42.860
Now where would food be heated?
 

00:13:42.860 --> 00:13:46.509
Well, it's commonly heated when
it's processed or when it's

00:13:46.509 --> 00:13:47.389
pasteurized.
 

00:13:47.389 --> 00:13:51.152
So when you take an apple and
you grind it up and you squeeze

00:13:51.152 --> 00:13:54.100
all the juice out of it to make
apple juice,

00:13:54.100 --> 00:13:59.563
it's commonly heated up for the
purposes of killing bacteria and

00:13:59.563 --> 00:14:01.820
protecting human health.
 

00:14:01.820 --> 00:14:05.423
Apple juice in the 1980s was
also exploding into the

00:14:05.423 --> 00:14:08.957
marketplace, in part because of
different packaging

00:14:08.957 --> 00:14:10.158
technologies.
 

00:14:10.158 --> 00:14:13.928
So it used to be available in
large glass bottles,

00:14:13.928 --> 00:14:18.264
but the advent of juice boxes
so that children would take

00:14:18.264 --> 00:14:22.832
these flavored juices to school
on a routine basis in really

00:14:22.832 --> 00:14:26.240
small cardboard and plastic
containers,

00:14:26.240 --> 00:14:29.639
it caused apple juice
consumption to skyrocket.

00:14:29.639 --> 00:14:33.421
So that apple juice,
within a matter of a decade,

00:14:33.421 --> 00:14:37.595
became one of the more heavily
consumed foods by young

00:14:37.595 --> 00:14:38.620
children.
 

00:14:38.620 --> 00:14:42.615
So it was introduced by
Uniroyal in 1966 and registered

00:14:42.615 --> 00:14:46.388
by the Department of
Agriculture, because EPA wasn't

00:14:46.388 --> 00:14:48.460
in existence until 1970.
 

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:52.474
And in 1973,
it was found to produce cancer

00:14:52.474 --> 00:14:53.428
in mice.
 

00:14:53.428 --> 00:14:57.009
Between 1977 and '78,
the National Cancer Institute

00:14:57.009 --> 00:14:59.730
found that that study was
credible,

00:14:59.730 --> 00:15:02.985
and they conducted their own
studies that found carcinogenic

00:15:02.985 --> 00:15:06.241
effects in animals,
raising the question how should

00:15:06.241 --> 00:15:08.678
we look at data from animal
testing?

00:15:08.678 --> 00:15:12.308
And what should we infer from
that about human health risk?

00:15:12.308 --> 00:15:15.360
Well, during conservative
political administrations,

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:19.522
we've tended as a society not
to worry too much about these

00:15:19.522 --> 00:15:22.678
low level cancer risks in the
food supply.

00:15:22.678 --> 00:15:24.570
But remember that at this point
in time,

00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:28.288
the Delaney Clause in the Food,
Drug and Cosmetic Act was in

00:15:28.288 --> 00:15:31.817
place that had what was called
the de minimis risk

00:15:31.817 --> 00:15:33.519
standard built into it.
 

00:15:33.519 --> 00:15:36.998
So it also had the Food and
Drug Administration that was

00:15:36.998 --> 00:15:40.222
interpreting the de
minimis standard to allow

00:15:40.222 --> 00:15:42.879
low levels of risk in the food
supply.

00:15:42.879 --> 00:15:47.183
So EPA concluded eventually in
1980 that it was carcinogenic

00:15:47.183 --> 00:15:50.904
and then negotiated with
Uniroyal for several years,

00:15:50.904 --> 00:15:53.240
and that produced no action.
 

00:15:53.240 --> 00:15:56.200
In 1985, they found that both
Alar,

00:15:56.200 --> 00:15:59.019
which is the parent compound
and the metabolite,

00:15:59.019 --> 00:16:02.259
the UDMH, was a "probable
human" carcinogen.

00:16:02.259 --> 00:16:05.009
So this is the next step up in
the level of concern.

00:16:05.009 --> 00:16:07.303
It's not just an animal
carcinogen--it's "probable

00:16:07.303 --> 00:16:07.899
human."
 

00:16:07.899 --> 00:16:10.207
The next step up,
by the way, is "known

00:16:10.207 --> 00:16:11.548
human carcinogen."
 

00:16:11.548 --> 00:16:15.221
And there are more than a
hundred now compounds that are

00:16:15.221 --> 00:16:18.158
characterized as known human
carcinogens,

00:16:18.158 --> 00:16:21.326
such as benzene and
1,3-butadiene,

00:16:21.326 --> 00:16:27.658
which exists in diesel exhaust
and other combustion situations,

00:16:27.658 --> 00:16:32.678
such as in wood smoke,
or virtually any time fossil

00:16:32.678 --> 00:16:35.288
fuel is being combusted.
 

00:16:35.288 --> 00:16:38.217
And in 1985,
some feedback from their own

00:16:38.217 --> 00:16:42.758
scientific advisory panel raised
questions about the quality of

00:16:42.758 --> 00:16:43.710
the data.
 

00:16:43.710 --> 00:16:46.919
Can you actually calculate a
cancer risk?

00:16:46.919 --> 00:16:49.678
So what is the threat?
 

00:16:49.678 --> 00:16:52.350
And what can publicly be stated
about that threat?

00:16:52.350 --> 00:16:54.168
Well, the Natural Resources
Defense Council,

00:16:54.168 --> 00:16:56.370
one of our largest
environmental groups,

00:16:56.370 --> 00:16:59.558
conducted their own analysis of
kids' exposure,

00:16:59.558 --> 00:17:02.585
recognizing that kids were
eating a lot of apples and

00:17:02.585 --> 00:17:05.318
applesauce and drinking a lot of
apple juice.

00:17:05.318 --> 00:17:10.930
It was a very common drink to
be served to infants in place of

00:17:10.930 --> 00:17:13.230
infant formula or milk.
 

00:17:13.230 --> 00:17:16.400
And has the EPA violated the
public trust?

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:20.980
So let me see if I can get this
going.

00:17:20.980 --> 00:17:25.173
This is a 60 Minutes
report that was prepared on

00:17:25.173 --> 00:17:26.650
this controversy.
 

00:17:26.650 --> 00:17:29.734
So that the Natural Resources
Defense Council brought their

00:17:29.734 --> 00:17:32.130
study to 60 Minutes and
asked them,

00:17:32.130 --> 00:17:35.268
"Would you like to release
this information on your

00:17:35.268 --> 00:17:36.009
show?"
 

00:17:36.009 --> 00:17:47.940
And the answer was yes.
 

00:17:47.940 --> 00:17:50.848
Ed Bradley [on video]:
 &gt;

00:17:50.848 --> 00:17:53.880
