00:22:37.941 --> 00:22:39.009
acceptable.
 

00:22:39.009 --> 00:22:41.077
Jack Moore [on video]:
 Risk unacceptable,

00:22:41.077 --> 00:22:43.319
yet magnitude of risk is less
by our calculation than

00:22:43.319 --> 00:22:44.568
&gt;
 

00:22:44.568 --> 00:22:53.655
Ed Bradley [on video]:
 Dr. John Grave a

00:22:53.655 --> 00:22:58.890
professor of--
Prof: I'm sorry,

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:00.950
this will take just one second.
 

00:23:00.950 --> 00:23:13.125
**
So think about what Janet

00:23:13.125 --> 00:23:15.890
Hathaway, the senior attorney
just said.

00:23:15.890 --> 00:23:18.782
"Over a lifetime,
one child out of every 4,000 or

00:23:18.782 --> 00:23:21.894
so of our preschoolers will
develop cancer from just these

00:23:21.894 --> 00:23:23.368
eight pesticides."
 

00:23:23.368 --> 00:23:25.990
Think about the wording,
the phrasing very carefully.

00:23:25.990 --> 00:23:27.778
This is quantitative risk
assessment.

00:23:27.778 --> 00:23:30.548
It's loaded with uncertainty
from many different sources.

00:23:30.548 --> 00:23:34.098
You're forced to infer from
animal evidence.

00:23:34.098 --> 00:23:38.141
You're forced to understand the
pattern of exposure,

00:23:38.141 --> 00:23:42.420
how the compound might behave
inside the human body.

00:23:42.420 --> 00:23:44.943
Then she said, "Alar,
the most potent cancer causing

00:23:44.943 --> 00:23:47.442
agent in our food supply,
is a substance sprayed on

00:23:47.442 --> 00:23:50.349
apples to keep them on the trees
longer...And what we're talking

00:23:50.349 --> 00:23:53.163
about is a cancer-causing agent
used on food that EPA knows is

00:23:53.163 --> 00:23:55.794
going to cause cancer for
thousands of children over their

00:23:55.794 --> 00:23:56.808
lifetime."
 

00:23:56.808 --> 00:24:02.405
These are statements of
certainty that caused widespread

00:24:02.405 --> 00:24:04.950
fear in the population.
 

00:24:04.950 --> 00:24:09.480
Senator Joe Lieberman spoke to
me during this situation.

00:24:09.480 --> 00:24:11.741
And he said he walked
immediately, after watching

00:24:11.741 --> 00:24:13.910
60 Minutes,
over to his refrigerator.

00:24:13.910 --> 00:24:17.233
He took out his jar of apple
juice and dumped it down the

00:24:17.233 --> 00:24:19.548
drain and started making phone
calls.

00:24:19.548 --> 00:24:22.401
This happened all over the
country as millions of people

00:24:22.401 --> 00:24:23.490
had witnessed this.
 

00:24:23.490 --> 00:24:28.210
Jack Moore, who you saw,
the acting EPA administrator,

00:24:28.210 --> 00:24:32.059
said that the evidence,
yes, that he relied upon was

00:24:32.059 --> 00:24:35.987
suitable for a decision to say
that Alar indeed was a

00:24:35.987 --> 00:24:37.118
carcinogen.
 

00:24:37.118 --> 00:24:39.798
And the media reaction was
really quite striking.

00:24:39.798 --> 00:24:43.236
All of the major media outlets
picked this story up,

00:24:43.236 --> 00:24:45.190
Newsweek,
et cetera.

00:24:45.190 --> 00:24:47.875
Donahue, on The Donahue
Show, he said "Don't

00:24:47.875 --> 00:24:50.170
look now, but we're poisoning
our kids."

00:24:50.170 --> 00:24:53.874
The consumer reaction was
really quite rapid and

00:24:53.874 --> 00:24:56.788
devastating for the apple
industry.

00:24:56.788 --> 00:24:59.682
Apple product sales dropped
thirty percent in a month,

00:24:59.682 --> 00:25:01.318
particularly on apple juice.
 

00:25:01.318 --> 00:25:04.403
School boards in New York and
Virginia and California stopped

00:25:04.403 --> 00:25:06.509
serving apples in their lunch
programs.

00:25:06.509 --> 00:25:11.380
Growers claimed losses of $250
million and they engaged in a

00:25:11.380 --> 00:25:15.673
lawsuit against both 60
Minutes as well as the

00:25:15.673 --> 00:25:18.808
Natural Resources Defense
Council.

00:25:18.808 --> 00:25:23.000
Within a matter of six months,
the economic concerns were so

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:26.836
high that the industry itself
was begging EPA to please

00:25:26.836 --> 00:25:30.460
regulate and prohibit the use of
this chemical.

00:25:30.460 --> 00:25:32.558
Now, that's really quite
striking.

00:25:32.558 --> 00:25:36.132
So that you've got really kind
of a very different type of

00:25:36.132 --> 00:25:37.700
regulatory theory here.
 

00:25:37.700 --> 00:25:39.858
What is regulation doing?
 

00:25:39.858 --> 00:25:43.752
It's really providing a sense
of legitimacy to manufacturers

00:25:43.752 --> 00:25:47.448
of different kinds of products
so that if you know that a

00:25:47.448 --> 00:25:50.515
chemical or a product,
it could be a food,

00:25:50.515 --> 00:25:51.798
it could be a car.
 

00:25:51.798 --> 00:25:55.880
If you know that it's been
reviewed by a regulatory agency,

00:25:55.880 --> 00:26:00.016
that act of regulation really
constitutes certification of

00:26:00.016 --> 00:26:04.660
that product's utility and also
its safety in the marketplace.

00:26:04.660 --> 00:26:08.442
So the fact that the growers
and the grocery stores and even

00:26:08.442 --> 00:26:11.905
Uniroyal asked EPA to move
quickly so that the economic

00:26:11.905 --> 00:26:15.432
damage would be limited and
consumer confidence could be

00:26:15.432 --> 00:26:17.883
restored,
particularly because this

00:26:17.883 --> 00:26:20.390
product was not used on all
apple products.

00:26:20.390 --> 00:26:22.494
So it really is a form of
symbolic politics,

00:26:22.494 --> 00:26:24.160
which I think is quite
striking.

00:26:24.160 --> 00:26:28.551
So that regardless of whether
or not the regulations are

00:26:28.551 --> 00:26:31.856
health protective,
they create a sense of

00:26:31.856 --> 00:26:36.000
legitimacy of products and
services in the marketplace so

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:40.468
that in one sense,
our corporations need these

00:26:40.468 --> 00:26:46.038
regulations so that they create
consumer confidence.

00:26:46.038 --> 00:26:49.202
So the Washington apple
growers, there are 4,700 of

00:26:49.202 --> 00:26:50.551
them,
claimed that well,

00:26:50.551 --> 00:26:53.218
there was no evidence linking
Alar to human cancer and the

00:26:53.218 --> 00:26:54.950
animal evidence was
insufficient,

00:26:54.950 --> 00:27:00.036
and they called this a product
disparagement or a trade libel

00:27:00.036 --> 00:27:00.630
case.
 

00:27:00.630 --> 00:27:03.974
And in this situation,
the growers faced the burden of

00:27:03.974 --> 00:27:04.480
proof.
 

00:27:04.480 --> 00:27:08.422
So they needed to prove that
the statements were made

00:27:08.422 --> 00:27:11.529
knowingly to be false,
the statements were

00:27:11.529 --> 00:27:15.170
deliberately made to induce
monetary damage.

00:27:15.170 --> 00:27:20.068
And this is a form of trade
libel law, defamation.

00:27:20.068 --> 00:27:24.319
So there are several forms of
libel, slander,

00:27:24.319 --> 00:27:25.769
and sedition.
 

00:27:25.769 --> 00:27:28.472
Libel, the definition is
defamation through print

00:27:28.472 --> 00:27:29.150
materials.
 

00:27:29.150 --> 00:27:31.390
Slander is oral defamation.
 

00:27:31.390 --> 00:27:34.924
In the English common law
tradition, libel in private

00:27:34.924 --> 00:27:38.529
enterprise generally found
favorably to plaintiffs.

00:27:38.529 --> 00:27:40.367
And sedition,
you'll recall,

00:27:40.367 --> 00:27:44.521
is any political criticism that
tended to diminish respect for

00:27:44.521 --> 00:27:47.450
government, laws,
and public officials.

00:27:47.450 --> 00:27:52.718
The common law definition of
libel was decided by a famous

00:27:52.718 --> 00:27:54.660
court case in 1933.
 

00:27:54.660 --> 00:27:57.182
It covers "all written
communications that tend to

00:27:57.182 --> 00:28:00.170
expose one to public hatred,
shame, obloquy,

00:28:00.170 --> 00:28:03.150
contumely, odium,
contempt,

00:28:03.150 --> 00:28:06.519
ridicule, aversion,
ostracism, degradation,

00:28:06.519 --> 00:28:09.058
or disgrace,
and to induce an evil opinion

00:28:09.058 --> 00:28:12.218
of one in the minds of
right-thinking persons and to

00:28:12.218 --> 00:28:15.810
deprive one of their confidence
and friendly intercourse in

00:28:15.810 --> 00:28:17.048
society."
 

00:28:17.048 --> 00:28:19.855
Well in this case,
the Ninth Circuit Court of

00:28:19.855 --> 00:28:23.617
Appeals found on the absence of
human studies that "The

00:28:23.617 --> 00:28:27.251
fact that there had been no
studies conducted specifically

00:28:27.251 --> 00:28:30.759
on the cancer risks to children
form daminozide,

00:28:30.759 --> 00:28:32.940
one of the arguments on the
part of the industry,

00:28:32.940 --> 00:28:35.497
does nothing to disprove the
conclusion that if children

00:28:35.497 --> 00:28:38.240
consume more of a carcinogenic
substance than do adults,

00:28:38.240 --> 00:28:40.940
they are at higher risk for
contracting cancer."

00:28:40.940 --> 00:28:43.884
So what's interesting about
this comment by the appellate

00:28:43.884 --> 00:28:46.618
court is that they're not
looking for proof that this

00:28:46.618 --> 00:28:48.670
chemical caused cancer in
children.

00:28:48.670 --> 00:28:53.618
They're looking for elevated
cancer risk.

00:28:53.618 --> 00:28:56.579
And on the falsity of the
statements, a product

00:28:56.579 --> 00:29:00.700
disparagement plaintiff has the
burden of proving the falsity.

00:29:00.700 --> 00:29:04.265
And this statement refers to
individuals, not to any overall

00:29:04.265 --> 00:29:04.868
message.
 

00:29:04.868 --> 00:29:07.458
And if a jury were given the
task of interpreting the

00:29:07.458 --> 00:29:09.996
uncertainty of a message,
it raises the specter of a

00:29:09.996 --> 00:29:11.490
chilling effect on speech.
 

00:29:11.490 --> 00:29:16.194
So think about the relationship
between this type of a court

00:29:16.194 --> 00:29:20.901
case and the freedom of the
individual to express themselves

00:29:20.901 --> 00:29:25.208
or express their opinion about
the dangers of different

00:29:25.208 --> 00:29:27.920
products or human behaviors.
 

00:29:27.920 --> 00:29:32.115
So this case was decided by the
Ninth Circuit fundamentally on a

00:29:32.115 --> 00:29:36.113
First Amendment choice referring
back to a famous New York

00:29:36.113 --> 00:29:38.844
Times v. Sullivan
case in 1964,

00:29:38.844 --> 00:29:41.855
where Sullivan,
who was a police commissioner

00:29:41.855 --> 00:29:44.679
in Alabama brought a libel
action against four African

00:29:44.679 --> 00:29:47.288
American clergy and the New
York Times.

00:29:47.288 --> 00:29:52.304
The Times had published
an advertisement back in 1960 in

00:29:52.304 --> 00:29:56.430
support of civil rights activism
among students,

00:29:56.430 --> 00:30:00.406
a struggle for the right to
vote, a legal defense of Martin

00:30:00.406 --> 00:30:03.150
Luther King against a perjury
charge,

00:30:03.150 --> 00:30:05.930
and charges of repressive
police misconduct,

00:30:05.930 --> 00:30:07.548
including false statements.
 

00:30:07.548 --> 00:30:11.057
And the trial judge had
instructed the jury that the

00:30:11.057 --> 00:30:15.253
advertisement was libelous,
that legal injury was implied,

00:30:15.253 --> 00:30:18.028
that falsity and malice are
presumed,

00:30:18.028 --> 00:30:21.160
and that punitive damages
should be awarded.

00:30:21.160 --> 00:30:24.353
So that in this case,
the Supreme Court found that it

00:30:24.353 --> 00:30:28.160
was constitutionally deficient
for failure to safeguard freedom

00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:31.967
of speech in the press required
by the First and the Fourteenth

00:30:31.967 --> 00:30:32.950
Amendment.
 

00:30:32.950 --> 00:30:35.009
And debate on public issues
should be uninhibited,

00:30:35.009 --> 00:30:37.373
robust, wide open,
and that it may well include

00:30:37.373 --> 00:30:40.135
vehement,
caustic, and sharp attacks on

00:30:40.135 --> 00:30:42.578
government and public officials.
 

00:30:42.578 --> 00:30:47.261
With respect to actual malice,
because in order to find

00:30:47.261 --> 00:30:51.077
disparagement or liability in
this situation,

00:30:51.077 --> 00:30:55.240
there's a need to demonstrate
actual malice.

00:30:55.240 --> 00:30:58.355
The constitutional guarantees
require a federal rule that

00:30:58.355 --> 00:31:01.361
prohibits a public official from
recovering damages for

00:31:01.361 --> 00:31:04.810
defamatory falsehood relating to
his official conduct unless he

00:31:04.810 --> 00:31:08.150
proves that the statement was
made with actual malice.

00:31:08.150 --> 00:31:09.880
What's malice?
 

00:31:09.880 --> 00:31:13.707
Well, it's with knowledge that
the claim was false when it was

00:31:13.707 --> 00:31:17.410
made, or with reckless disregard
of whether it was false.

00:31:17.410 --> 00:31:22.071
And the burden of demonstrating
the falsity rests on the

00:31:22.071 --> 00:31:23.088
plaintiff.
 

00:31:23.088 --> 00:31:28.896
Now, this seems to give the
media a fairly wide berth in the

00:31:28.896 --> 00:31:32.538
kinds of claims that they can
make.

00:31:32.538 --> 00:31:37.067
In the wake of this case,
many states passed what are

00:31:37.067 --> 00:31:41.420
thought of now and labeled as
veggie libel laws.

00:31:41.420 --> 00:31:46.458
So that rather than placing the
burden on a plaintiff to

00:31:46.458 --> 00:31:50.490
demonstrate the falsity of the
statement,

00:31:50.490 --> 00:31:54.087
they place the burden on the
individual that makes the claim

00:31:54.087 --> 00:31:56.038
of significant risk or hazard.
 

00:31:56.038 --> 00:32:00.640
So there are many states that
have adopted this statutory

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:01.380
change.
 

00:32:01.380 --> 00:32:06.099
And what this means is that it
opens the way for slap suits.

00:32:06.099 --> 00:32:07.710
What is a slap suit?
 

00:32:07.710 --> 00:32:12.076
It basically is a suit that
intimidates people from making

00:32:12.076 --> 00:32:16.597
claims about the quality of the
environment or causes of its

00:32:16.597 --> 00:32:19.509
loss or subsequent health
damages.

00:32:19.509 --> 00:32:23.190
So among these twenty or so
states that have adopted these

00:32:23.190 --> 00:32:26.226
laws, for example,
now I will not give a lecture

00:32:26.226 --> 00:32:28.680
where I am making a claim of
risk.

00:32:28.680 --> 00:32:31.982
So that might be thought of as
a chilling effect on free speech

00:32:31.982 --> 00:32:32.568
in a way.
 

00:32:32.568 --> 00:32:36.269
So if I'm, say,
being taped on a radio show,

00:32:36.269 --> 00:32:41.097
that radio show is broadcast in
a state where one of these

00:32:41.097 --> 00:32:46.182
veggie libel laws exists that
would place the burden on me to

00:32:46.182 --> 00:32:50.840
demonstrate the proof that my
claim is backed up by high

00:32:50.840 --> 00:32:54.597
quality science,
that will pull me into court,

00:32:54.597 --> 00:32:57.029
it will cost me thousands of
dollars,

00:32:57.029 --> 00:32:58.759
hundreds of thousands of
dollars even,

00:32:58.759 --> 00:33:02.490
to defend myself.
 

00:33:02.490 --> 00:33:07.153
So that the influence of this
form of law is really quite

00:33:07.153 --> 00:33:08.068
striking.
 

00:33:08.068 --> 00:33:12.144
What also is interesting about
this evolution of state laws

00:33:12.144 --> 00:33:16.570
that reverse the burden of proof
is that clearly it's been found

00:33:16.570 --> 00:33:20.855
by the Supreme Court as being an
unconstitutional shift in the

00:33:20.855 --> 00:33:21.769
burden.
 

00:33:21.769 --> 00:33:25.241
Yet none of these state laws
have been taken up to the

00:33:25.241 --> 00:33:27.470
Supreme Court for consideration.
 

00:33:27.470 --> 00:33:29.528
So think about that.
 

00:33:29.528 --> 00:33:32.608
These laws have been in place
now for well over a decade,

00:33:32.608 --> 00:33:36.441
and all environmental groups,
all public health interest

00:33:36.441 --> 00:33:40.760
groups understand the nature of
these laws and they're all very

00:33:40.760 --> 00:33:45.289
self-conscious about the nature
of the claims that they make.

00:33:45.289 --> 00:33:47.269
Now, I want to show you this.
 

00:33:47.269 --> 00:33:52.440
Oprah Winfrey hosted a show on
mad cow disease.

00:33:52.440 --> 00:33:57.686
Mad cow disease is an illness
that is caused by a prion and

00:33:57.686 --> 00:34:03.204
believed to be associated with
beef that are feed other cattle

00:34:03.204 --> 00:34:06.009
parts in their cattle meal.
 

00:34:06.009 --> 00:34:10.958
So Winfrey hosted Howard Lyman,
who described the process of

00:34:10.958 --> 00:34:15.655
slaughterhouses and beef
rendering and how the parts were

00:34:15.655 --> 00:34:20.519
ground up and then put into
animal feed and fed back in the

00:34:20.519 --> 00:34:25.050
United States to cattle that
were sold for food.

00:34:25.050 --> 00:34:29.628
And this was the mechanism that
he and others believed had

00:34:29.628 --> 00:34:34.289
caused the outbreak of mad cow
disease in Great Britain.

00:34:34.289 --> 00:34:37.030
Now there are laws that prevent
that from happening,

00:34:37.030 --> 00:34:41.206
but at this point in time,
this represents another rather

00:34:41.206 --> 00:34:44.489
interesting case on product
disparagement.

00:34:44.489 --> 00:35:02.539
** Give me one second
here.

00:35:02.539 --> 00:35:16.851
** I've lost my
internet connection,

00:35:16.851 --> 00:35:27.260
so we're on hold for a moment.
 

00:35:27.260 --> 00:36:15.880
** My apology for that
delay.

00:36:15.880 --> 00:36:18.199
Howard Lyman [on video]:
 With me on the stage,

00:36:18.199 --> 00:36:21.418
to the left of me a grandmother
whose granddaughter is dying of

00:36:21.418 --> 00:36:23.860
the human form of mad cow
disease in England.

00:36:23.860 --> 00:36:26.887
To the right of me,
a guy from the National Cattle

00:36:26.887 --> 00:36:29.563
and Beef Association,
points at me and says

00:36:29.563 --> 00:36:33.092
"Here is a man who believes
within ten years we could have

00:36:33.092 --> 00:36:36.449
diseases that make AIDS look
like the common cold."

00:36:36.449 --> 00:36:38.949
And I said, absolutely.
 

00:36:38.949 --> 00:36:40.215
And she said,
"That's such a strong

00:36:40.215 --> 00:36:40.800
statement."
 

00:36:40.800 --> 00:36:44.117
I said, "Oprah,
we have 100,000 cows a year

00:36:44.117 --> 00:36:46.800
alive at night,
dead in the morning.

00:36:46.800 --> 00:36:48.920
We round them up,
grind them up,

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:52.480
turn them into feed,
feed them back to other cows.

00:36:52.480 --> 00:36:54.911
We go out and collect road
kill, deer, elk,

00:36:54.911 --> 00:36:57.342
possum, raccoons,
scrape them up off of the

00:36:57.342 --> 00:37:00.469
street, grind them up,
and feed them back to cows.

00:37:00.469 --> 00:37:03.340
And then we take pets,
city of Los Angeles,

00:37:03.340 --> 00:37:06.994
200 tons of pets,
full of chemicals that were

00:37:06.994 --> 00:37:10.717
used to kill them,
200 tons a month are ground up,

00:37:10.717 --> 00:37:13.733
turned into feed,
and fed back to our food

00:37:13.733 --> 00:37:14.860
animals."
 

00:37:14.860 --> 00:37:18.030
This time Oprah's eyes are as
big as saucers.

00:37:18.030 --> 00:37:21.309
I knew that I'd got her.
 

00:37:21.309 --> 00:37:25.322
She turns around and looks at
the guy from the National Cattle

00:37:25.322 --> 00:37:28.347
and Beef Association and says,
"Dr. Weber,

00:37:28.347 --> 00:37:30.980
are we feeding cows to
cows?"

00:37:30.980 --> 00:37:34.090
I'll never **
what he had to say,

00:37:34.090 --> 00:37:37.014
he said, "Well,
you know, there's a limited

00:37:37.014 --> 00:37:39.130
amount of that going on."
 

00:37:39.130 --> 00:37:42.250
I believe that about
ninety-five percent of the

00:37:42.250 --> 00:37:46.387
cattle fed back in factory feed
lots are eating the remains of

00:37:46.387 --> 00:37:47.610
other animals.
 

00:37:47.610 --> 00:37:52.420
And the next thing out of
Oprah's mouth then gets us sued.

00:37:52.420 --> 00:37:55.909
Oprah says, "That just
stops me cold.

00:37:55.909 --> 00:37:59.340
I will never again eat a
burger."

00:37:59.340 --> 00:38:04.150
Now, she didn't say,
"I think the meat's

00:38:04.150 --> 00:38:06.010
infected."
 

00:38:06.010 --> 00:38:09.161
She didn't say to the millions
of viewers, "You shouldn't

00:38:09.161 --> 00:38:09.989
eat any."
 

00:38:09.989 --> 00:38:12.760
She just said,
"That stops me cold.

00:38:12.760 --> 00:38:15.460
I will never again eat a
burger."

00:38:15.460 --> 00:38:19.456
Now I knew when I went on that
show that thirteen states had a

00:38:19.456 --> 00:38:22.210
thing called the food
disparagement law.

00:38:22.210 --> 00:38:26.972
The food disparagement law says
that it's against the law to say

00:38:26.972 --> 00:38:31.659
something you know to be false
about a perishable commodity.

00:38:31.659 --> 00:38:35.309
I didn't say anything I thought
to be false.

00:38:35.309 --> 00:38:40.170
I told the truth.
 

00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:44.739
Well, we were taping the show,
took about two hours.

00:38:44.739 --> 00:38:47.576
When we got done taping the
show I walked up to Oprah and I

00:38:47.576 --> 00:38:49.974
said to her,
I said, "Hey Oprah,

00:38:49.974 --> 00:38:53.360
give me ten minutes,
I'll get you off of

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:54.829
chicken."
 

00:38:54.829 --> 00:38:57.257
Oprah looked at me and said,
"Only one animal a

00:38:57.257 --> 00:38:57.829
day."
 

00:38:57.829 --> 00:39:00.329
&lt;&lt;audience
laughter&gt;&gt;

00:39:00.329 --> 00:39:04.380
So, I went about my business.
 

00:39:04.380 --> 00:39:06.650
Couple weeks later,
I got a call that said,

00:39:06.650 --> 00:39:09.576
"Do you realize you're
being sued with Oprah Winfrey

00:39:09.576 --> 00:39:12.659
and Harpo Production by a group
of Texas cattlemen?"

00:39:12.659 --> 00:39:15.760
And I said, "No,
can I put you on hold?"

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:19.038
I raced into my library,
I inventoried my vegetarian

00:39:19.038 --> 00:39:19.809
cookbooks.
 

00:39:19.809 --> 00:39:24.760
I knew those cattlemen wanted
those vegetarian cookbooks bad.

00:39:24.760 --> 00:39:27.327
I went back and said,
"I can't talk to you right

00:39:27.327 --> 00:39:29.699
now, I've got to put in a call
to Oprah."

00:39:29.699 --> 00:39:32.909
I called Oprah and left a
message, and I said,

00:39:32.909 --> 00:39:35.262
"Oprah,
if we lose this suit,

00:39:35.262 --> 00:39:38.829
I'm going to throw in my
vegetarian cookbooks.

00:39:38.829 --> 00:39:41.610
You've got to put up the
money."

00:39:41.610 --> 00:39:46.500
Well, we end up getting sued in
Amarillo, Texas.

00:39:46.500 --> 00:39:50.288
I don't know how many of you
have ever been to Amarillo,

00:39:50.288 --> 00:39:50.840
Texas.
 

00:39:50.840 --> 00:39:55.956
It's not the end of the world,
but it's clearly visible from

00:39:55.956 --> 00:39:56.650
there.
 

00:39:56.650 --> 00:40:01.141
If you're going to give the
world an enema you take the hose

00:40:01.141 --> 00:40:02.739
to Amarillo, Texas.
 

00:40:02.739 --> 00:40:06.181
The largest employer in
Amarillo, Texas,

00:40:06.181 --> 00:40:10.949
happens to be the slaughter
facility killing cattle.

00:40:10.949 --> 00:40:15.755
Bumper stickers all over town
said, "The only mad cow in

00:40:15.755 --> 00:40:18.079
Texas is named Oprah."
 

00:40:18.079 --> 00:40:21.501
I knew we were in trouble when
I went and saw my lawyer,

00:40:21.501 --> 00:40:24.177
and I said to him,
"We need a change of

00:40:24.177 --> 00:40:24.800
venue.
 

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:28.893
There is no way in the world
that we can win here in

00:40:28.893 --> 00:40:30.260
Amarillo."
 

00:40:30.260 --> 00:40:34.849
So we filed with the judge for
a change of venue.

00:40:34.849 --> 00:40:38.039
We walked in, who's the judge?
 

00:40:38.039 --> 00:40:42.480
Seventy-two-year-old lady,
a tough old heifer.

00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:45.623
We asked for a change of venue,
she picks up the hammer,

00:40:45.623 --> 00:40:48.309
slaps it down,
and says, "Motion denied.

00:40:48.309 --> 00:40:50.510
Bring in the jury pool."
 

00:40:50.510 --> 00:40:52.420
They brought 140 people in.
 

00:40:52.420 --> 00:40:55.782
You never saw so many hats,
boots, and belt buckles in all

00:40:55.782 --> 00:40:56.489
your life.
 

00:40:56.489 --> 00:40:58.954
I said to my lawyer,
"We need to find an

00:40:58.954 --> 00:41:02.425
appeal, because there's no way
in the world that we're going to

00:41:02.425 --> 00:41:03.489
win here."
 

00:41:03.489 --> 00:41:06.980
At the end of the day,
we had twelve jurors,

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:10.469
absolutely steeped in the
cattle culture.

00:41:10.469 --> 00:41:16.275
My lawyer, he looks at me and
he said, "They're going to

00:41:16.275 --> 00:41:20.050
call you to the stand
tomorrow."

00:41:20.050 --> 00:41:23.454
He said, "The first
question they're going to ask

00:41:23.454 --> 00:41:26.730
you is whether or not you are a
vegetarian."

00:41:26.730 --> 00:41:28.780
I said, "I can handle
that."

00:41:28.780 --> 00:41:33.179
He said, "You damn well
better, you'll lose."

00:41:33.179 --> 00:41:35.202
Sure enough,
the next day they called me to

00:41:35.202 --> 00:41:35.780
the stand.
 

00:41:35.780 --> 00:41:38.630
I'm on the stand with the
plaintiff's attorney is looking

00:41:38.630 --> 00:41:40.210
at me, laughing and giggling.
 

00:41:40.210 --> 00:41:43.679
And he says,
"I can't hardly say this.

00:41:43.679 --> 00:41:47.255
Hey, Mr. Lyman,
is it true that you are a--

00:41:47.255 --> 00:41:49.469
&gt;
 

00:41:49.469 --> 00:41:51.400
--a vegetarian?"
 

00:41:51.400 --> 00:41:55.148
And I looked at the jury and
said, "I will not apologize

00:41:55.148 --> 00:41:57.960
for something that has saved my
life."

00:41:57.960 --> 00:42:03.585
Never again in that trial did
they ever ask me about why I was

00:42:03.585 --> 00:42:04.969
a vegetarian.
 

00:42:04.969 --> 00:42:08.619
But they asked me every
question you can imagine.

00:42:08.619 --> 00:42:11.550
I'm on the stand,
the lawyer looks at me and he

00:42:11.550 --> 00:42:14.672
says, "Mr. Lyman,
has anybody ever called you

00:42:14.672 --> 00:42:16.329
irresponsible?"
 

00:42:16.329 --> 00:42:18.170
I said, "Yes."
 

00:42:18.170 --> 00:42:22.257
My lawyer's sitting over there
going, "No,

00:42:22.257 --> 00:42:23.590
no, no."
 

00:42:23.590 --> 00:42:26.641
The plaintiff's attorney thinks
he's found the key to the

00:42:26.641 --> 00:42:27.460
Gordian Knot.
 

00:42:27.460 --> 00:42:29.900
And he looks at me and he says,
"Who?"

00:42:29.900 --> 00:42:32.119
I said, "My wife."
 

00:42:32.119 --> 00:42:36.929
And the jury's over there,
been there, done that.

00:42:36.929 --> 00:42:40.000
We were in that courtroom for
six weeks.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:44.577
At the end of six weeks,
that jury found Oprah,

00:42:44.577 --> 00:42:48.659
Harpo Production and myself not
liable.

00:42:48.659 --> 00:42:51.219
The plaintiffs went out of
their tree.

00:42:51.219 --> 00:42:56.900
They could not imagine that
that jury, that homegrown jury,

00:42:56.900 --> 00:43:00.719
could find out-of-towners not
liable.

00:43:00.719 --> 00:43:05.360
And they appealed with the
Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals.

00:43:05.360 --> 00:43:08.489
We spent a year in the Fifth
Circuit Court of Appeals.

00:43:08.489 --> 00:43:12.487
And at the end of the year,
they came down with a unanimous

00:43:12.487 --> 00:43:16.141
panel decision that Oprah,
Harpo Production and myself

00:43:16.141 --> 00:43:17.518
were not liable.
 

00:43:17.518 --> 00:43:21.630
And then they wrote an opinion
that said,

00:43:21.630 --> 00:43:26.431
"Everything that Lyman
said on the show was true and

00:43:26.431 --> 00:43:29.518
the truth is not
actionable."

00:43:29.518 --> 00:43:32.076
The cattlemen couldn't stand
that and asked

00:43:32.076 --> 00:43:33.719
&gt;
 

00:43:33.719 --> 00:43:35.599
for a rehearing.
 

00:43:35.599 --> 00:43:37.449
It was denied.
 

00:43:37.449 --> 00:43:41.447
And then the cattlemen got
together and went to state court

00:43:41.447 --> 00:43:45.306
and filed suit against Oprah,
Harpo Production and myself

00:43:45.306 --> 00:43:47.030
with the state court.
 

00:43:47.030 --> 00:43:49.309
Thank God I did not live in
Texas.

00:43:49.309 --> 00:43:52.844
I was able to move it from the
state court to the federal

00:43:52.844 --> 00:43:53.349
court.
 

00:43:53.349 --> 00:43:54.449
They appealed that.
 

00:43:54.449 --> 00:43:57.771
We spent six years,
hundreds of thousands of

00:43:57.771 --> 00:44:02.329
dollars of my money defending
&gt;

00:44:02.329 --> 00:44:05.150
to tell the truth.
 

00:44:05.150 --> 00:44:09.769
At the end of six years the
judge finally threw out the case

00:44:09.769 --> 00:44:12.760
with prejudice,
which meant the jury,

00:44:12.760 --> 00:44:16.300
or the plaintiffs could not
re-file the case,

00:44:16.300 --> 00:44:22.360
that the statute of limitations
had run out.

00:44:22.360 --> 00:44:30.976
So it became six years,
hundreds of thousands of

00:44:30.976 --> 00:44:40.876
dollars, we were finally
vindicated for standing up and

00:44:40.876 --> 00:44:44.909
telling the truth.
 

00:44:44.909 --> 00:44:47.844
Prof: So the core of
this problem is the way that

00:44:47.844 --> 00:44:50.940
these state veggie libel laws
shift the burden of proof.

00:44:50.940 --> 00:44:54.436
So under federal law,
it's really clear that the

00:44:54.436 --> 00:44:58.527
Cattlemen's Association was
under the burden of proof to

00:44:58.527 --> 00:45:02.471
demonstrate that the statement
was knowingly false and

00:45:02.471 --> 00:45:06.340
delivered with malice with the
intent to harm.

00:45:06.340 --> 00:45:09.893
But under state law,
Oprah's burden was to

00:45:09.893 --> 00:45:14.485
demonstrate that the statement
is true with reasonable

00:45:14.485 --> 00:45:15.699
certainty.
 

00:45:15.699 --> 00:45:18.900
So I'll leave you with one
thought on this,

00:45:18.900 --> 00:45:22.358
and the importance of
fashioning law in a way that

00:45:22.358 --> 00:45:26.666
would protect free speech and
open access to knowledge of risk

00:45:26.666 --> 00:45:29.489
and opinions on the part of
experts.

00:45:29.489 --> 00:45:32.257
Justice Powell,
in 1974 on truth and free

00:45:32.257 --> 00:45:34.076
speech,
"There's no such thing as

00:45:34.076 --> 00:45:36.248
a false idea,
no matter how pernicious an

00:45:36.248 --> 00:45:39.635
opinion may seem,
we depend its correction not on

00:45:39.635 --> 00:45:42.400
the conscience of judges and
juries,

00:45:42.400 --> 00:45:45.519
but on the competition of other
ideas."

00:45:45.519 --> 00:45:46.599
So that's it for today.
 

00:45:46.599 --> 00:45:47.639
Have a great weekend.
 

00:45:47.639 --> 00:45:53.000
 
 

